       title="SCU-LAN10" id="SCU-LAN10">

    <p>I came close to buying an SCU-LAN10 network interface to go with my FTdx101D when I first purchased the radio.
    But when I researched the box, I understood that Yaesu had not released an API to permit third party applications
    to use it, and had limited the application that they supply to speech telephony only. </p>
    <p>A few years later, AI coding agents like Claude have developed beyond all expectations. I had seen a few comments on
    the web which suggested that other owners of the radio had had some success in reverse engineering the network
    protocol and I decided to risk the money, buy my own SCU-LAN10 and see how far I could get with it.</p>
    <p>It has been a bit of an uphill struggle, and it is still not perfect, but after around three weeks working with
    Claude, I now have a working API and 101Cats can operate my radio over a network connection pretty well.
    Claude is clever, but not a magician, and the internet restrictions that made Yaesu so wary of
    releasing a version of their application with an interface that is usable by applications such as WSJT-X
    still apply. But my experiments show that it is possible to do a lot, and I have successfully run
    WSJT-X over internet links including relatively slow 4G connections.
    </p>
    <p>At this stage, I would not encourage anyone to run out and buy a SCU-LAN10 solely on the promise that 101Cats will
    support it. The latest versions of 101Cats V2 do a decent job of it and are very usable. but the audio
    still fragments sometimes and I don't know how long it will be before I get that fixed. But if you have
    a SCU-LAN10 and are willing to experiment. I would welcome test reports. I will expand this page soon with
    installation and configuration instructions.</p>
</topic>